Midgaard's occult oversight framework, the Violet Compact, maintains the Null Spire Conductorate in its threat classification archive.
The classification is historical but active: institutions with Conductorate-derived methods would qualify for immediate Compact intervention under current charter.
The Conductorate's most directly relevant characteristic, from a Midgaard registry perspective, is that it made accountability structurally impossible through multi-office diffusion.
No single office authorized what happened. Each office authorized a part. The Conductorate authorized the pressure calibration. The Chancery authorized the testimony cycles. The Ten authorized the facility operations.
Each authorization was individually defensible. The combined effect was systematic harm without a single accountable decision.
Midgaard's charter review process includes a structural anti-diffusion requirement derived from this pattern: any multi-office operation must designate a single accountable authority for its combined effect.
This requirement was contested when proposed; the argument against it was that single-authority designation creates bottlenecks. The Continuity faction replied: the Conductorate is what you get when you avoid bottlenecks.
The Violet Compact's sealed-warrant oversight is partly justified by the Conductorate precedent: institutions that claim oversight authority over themselves cannot be trusted to exercise it.
External review requirements exist because the Conductorate's officers believed they were doing legitimate work. Some of them were correct about parts of it. None were correct about all of it.

